## Dev environments tips
- Always prioritise to use `{{ .PM }}` as package manager.
- Development PORT is set to `:3000` by default
- Always update README.md and AGENTS.md when new package and new script has been added
- Do not install packages unless nesccessary, practice less dependency
- Prioitise fixing/adding code in smaller chunk. 
- Add useful comments to document complex features / code changes, not generic comments

```bash
{{ .PM }} install       # install dependency
{{ .PM }} dev           # start dev server
{{ .PM }} build         # production build
{{ .PM }} preview       # preview build
{{ .PM }} format        # format and lint code
```

## Workflow
Use the information below as the standard workflow and criteria check-point:

- Always clarify with the user if the instruction is unclear 
- Always perform type check after code changes (can run `build`)
- Always ensure no errors show after code changes (can run `build`)
- Always ensure the test pass if test cases are provided (can run `test`)

## Memory

**Always keep memory up to date as you work.** Record decisions, conventions, gotchas, and project state in `.claude/memories/memory-*.md` (one topic per file, e.g. `.claude/memories/memory-auth.md`). Read existing memory files at the start of a task and update or add to them as you go — don't wait until the end.

## Wiki (Knowledge Base)

The `.wiki/` directory is the project's knowledge base and contains all project knowledge — specs, design docs, notes, reference PDFs, images, diagrams, and any other supporting material. Treat it as the source of truth for context: read relevant files there before starting a task, and add new knowledge to it as the project evolves.

## Secrets and sensitive data
- Never print secrets (tokens, private keys, credentials) to terminal output.
- Do not request users paste secrets.
- Avoid commands that might expose secrets (e.g., dumping env vars broadly, `cat ~/.ssh/*`).
- Prefer existing authenticated CLIs; redact sensitive strings in any displayed output.

## Code style

### General
- Keep components small and composable
- Prefer functional components
- Respect formatter (biome, prettier) configuration

### Typescript
- Typescript `strict` mode
- NEVER use `any` type, use `unknown` type
- AVOID using `as` assertion, always prioritise proper type casting / type guarding
- Prefer arrow function

### JSDoc Block - Documentation
Always include JSDoc block in the very begining of every `components`, `page`, `utils`, `hooks`. Refer to the template below.

#### General JSDoc Block template

```typescript
/**
 * [Module]: [Name]
 * 
 * @file [path/to/this/file]
 * @description [Simple one sentence description about this file].
 * @module [Module]
 */
```

Example:

```typescript
// .vue files
<script setup lang='ts'>
/**
 * Components: PrimaryButton
 * 
 * @file @/components/ui/primary-button.vue
 * @description Primary button to use for CTA.
 * @module Components
 */

// ...other codes
</script>


// hooks files
/**
 * Hooks: useCustomFetch
 *
 * @file @/hooks/useCustomFetch.ts
 * @description Reuseable fetch hook with custom setting.
 * @return success bool, message string
 * @module Hooks
 */
const useCustomFetch = (): { success: boolean, message: string } => {
  // ...other codes
}
```

## Project structure
- Always use `kebab-case` for naming convention
- Each project must have `/components`, `/pages`, `/libs`, `/data`. Refer to the template below for more details

### Components structure
```
/components
  /ui                   # primitives components (button, input, badge, select...)
  /layout               # layout components (header, nav, footer, sidebar...)
    /header
    /footer
  /page                 # per-page section components
    /top
    /about
    /company
    /contact-us
  /icon                 # inline icon components (svg)
```

### Layouts
```
/layouts                # all layouts across the site
  /default.{vue,tsx,astro}
```


### Hooks / Composables
```
/composables
  /useCustomFetch.ts
```

### Lib & Utils
```
/libs
  /utils.ts             # contains `cn()` and utils functions
  /styles.ts            # contains `cva` styles
```

### Types
```
/types
  /user.ts
  /product.ts           
```

### Data
```
/data                   # contains static data, or mocking data
  /userMock.ts
```
